(iStock) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Kalamazoo- A motorist accused of killing five bicyclists and injuring four others in southwestern Michigan will stand trial on second-degree murder charges.A Kalamazoo County Circuit judge in the US has denied Charles Pickett Jr's motion to reverse an earlier ruling that allowed the murder charges.The judge also denied Pickett's efforts to suppress statements he made to police about the crash.The nine bicyclists were struck on June 7 2016 by a pickup along a rural road in Cooper Township.Pickett also is charged with operating a motor vehicle while intoxicated causing death and causing serious injury.A state police scientist has said Pickett's blood tests after the crash revealed drugs, including painkillers and methamphetamine.An April 24 trial is scheduled. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.